👉 Redundant Connection (Union-Find Trick) (LeetCode 684)

Given a graph that was originally a tree,
one extra edge was added.

Return the edge that creates the cycle.

✨ Flashcard

“Build the tree edge by edge.
If two nodes already share a leader → cycle found.”

⚡ Full Mental Map (Very Easy)

This problem looks like graph theory,
but it’s really one simple idea:

1️⃣ Build connections gradually
2️⃣ Track connected components
3️⃣ The first edge that connects same component → redundant

That’s it.

🧠 Big Picture Strategy

❌ Bad idea
For every edge:
• Run DFS to check cycle
→ O(N²)

Too slow.

✅ Good idea
Use Union-Find to track connectivity in near O(1).

Union-Find answers one question fast:

“Are these two nodes already connected?”

🧩 Step 1: Initialize Disjoint Sets

We create:

• A parent for every node
• A rank (tree height)

Initially:

1   2   3   4
↑   ↑   ↑   ↑


Everyone is their own group.

🧠 Mental Map
“Everyone starts alone.”

🧩 Step 2: Process Edges One by One

We loop through edges in order:

For each edge (u, v):

Try to connect them.

🧩 Step 3: What Does Union Actually Do?

Union does two things:

1️⃣ Find root of u
2️⃣ Find root of v

If both roots are same:

⚠️ They’re already connected
⚠️ Adding this edge forms a cycle

Return False.

If different:

Attach one tree under the other (by rank).
Return True.

🧠 Mental Map

“Different leaders → merge groups.
Same leader → loop detected.”

🧩 Step 4: Path Compression (Hidden Speed Boost)

During find:

While climbing upward to find the root:

• Make nodes skip their parent
• Point them closer to root

Instead of:

1 → 2 → 3 → 4


It becomes:

1 → 4
2 → 4
3 → 4


Future finds become almost instant.

🧠 Mental Map

“Climb to the leader.
Shorten the ladder while climbing.”

🧩 Step 5: Why Returning Immediately Works

We process edges in input order.

The first time union fails:

That edge is the one that closes the cycle.

Problem says:

“If multiple answers exist, return the one that occurs last.”

Because:

• Earlier edges build the tree
• The last edge that closes the loop is the redundant one

Union-Find naturally detects it.

🧪 Example 1

Input:

[[1,2],[1,3],[2,3]]


Process:

• (1,2) → merge
• (1,3) → merge
• (2,3) → already connected

Return:

[2,3]

🧪 Example 2

Input:

[[1,2],[2,3],[3,4],[1,4],[1,5]]


Process:

• (1,2) merge
• (2,3) merge
• (3,4) merge
• (1,4) → already connected

Return:

[1,4]

⭐ Why This Works

Because in a tree:

• No cycles
• Exactly n-1 edges

Adding one more edge:

• Must create exactly one cycle

Union-Find detects exactly that moment.

📦 Complexity

Let:

• n = number of nodes

Time
Almost O(n)

(technically O(n α(n)))

Space
O(n)

🧠 One-Line Intuition

“While building the tree,
the first edge that connects two already-connected nodes
is the redundant edge.”

