Pop 2 → neighbors: 1,3
Heap: [(1,1),(1,3)]       dist: {1:1,2:0,3:1,4:inf}
Pop 1 → no neighbors
Pop 3 → neighbor 4
Heap: [(2,4)]             dist: {1:1,2:0,3:1,4:2}
Pop 4 → no neighbors

Network delay = 2 (last node receives signal at t=2)

🔑 Interview Tips

Always use a min-heap for efficiency (O(E log V))

Skip outdated distances (currDist > dist[node])

Network delay = max of all shortest distances

Return -1 if any node unreachable

🧠 One-Line Intuition

“Pick the closest node, spread the signal to neighbors updating shortest times, repeat until all nodes processed → largest distance = network delay.”

👉 Dijkstra on Grid – Swim in Rising Water (LeetCode 778)

Efficiently calculate the minimum time required to reach the bottom-right cell in a grid where water level rises over time.

Perfect when:

You have a grid with elevations

Movement is 4-directional

The “cost” of a path depends on the maximum value along the path

You want the minimum possible maximum

Classic min-heap Dijkstra variation

✨ Flashcard

Front:
“How do I find the minimum time to reach bottom-right in a rising water grid?”

Back:

Treat each cell as a graph node

Time to enter a cell = max(elevation so far, cell elevation)

Use a min-heap to always expand the lowest time cell

Mark visited when popped (finalized)

Stop when bottom-right is popped from heap

⚡ Step-by-Step Combined Explanation
1️⃣ Initialize Grid Info
n = len(grid)
visited = [[False] * n for _ in range(n)]

visited[r][c] → marks finalized cells

Just like dist[] in normal Dijkstra

Mental Map:
“Have we already processed this cell with minimum possible time?”

2️⃣ Setup Min Heap
minHeap = [(grid[0][0], 0, 0)]

Heap contains:

(time_needed, row, col)

Start at (0,0).

Why time = grid[0][0]?

Because water must rise at least to that elevation for you to stand there.

3️⃣ Directions (4 Moves)
directions = [(1, 0), (-1, 0), (0, 1), (0, -1)]

Allowed moves:

Down

Up

Right

Left

Mental Map:
“From each cell, try all four neighbors.”

4️⃣ Process Cells (Dijkstra Loop)
while minHeap:
    time, r, c = heapq.heappop(minHeap)

Pop the cell requiring the smallest time to reach.

Exactly like:

currDist, node = heapq.heappop(minHeap)

in Network Delay Time.

5️⃣ If Destination → Return
if r == n - 1 and c == n - 1:
    return time

Why return immediately?

Because:

Heap guarantees this is the minimum possible time to reach bottom-right.

Once popped → finalized → optimal.

6️⃣ Skip Already Visited
if visited[r][c]:
    continue
visited[r][c] = True

Same as:

if currDist > dist[node]: continue

We mark visited when popped because:

At that moment → we know this is the best possible time for that cell.

Mental Map:
“Lock this cell. We’ve reached it in minimum time.”

7️⃣ Explore Neighbors
for dr, dc in directions:
    nr, nc = r + dr, c + dc

Try all 4 adjacent cells.

Check Valid Move
if 0 <= nr < n and 0 <= nc < n and not visited[nr][nc]:

Ensure:

Inside grid

Not already finalized

8️⃣ Compute Time to Enter Neighbor
newTime = max(time, grid[nr][nc])

This is the KEY difference from normal Dijkstra.

Instead of:

newDist = currDist + weight

We do:

newTime = max(current_path_time, neighbor_elevation)

Why?

Because:

Water must be high enough for all previous cells

AND high enough for this new cell

So we take the larger of the two.

Mental Map:

“Earliest time water must rise so I can stand on this neighbor.”

9️⃣ Push into Heap
heapq.heappush(minHeap, (newTime, nr, nc))

We tell the heap:

“If water rises to newTime, I can reach (nr,nc).”

Heap keeps smallest time first.

🧠 Step-by-Step Dry Run

Example:

