👉 Longest Palindromic Substring (LeetCode 5)

Return the longest contiguous substring of s that is a palindrome.

A palindrome reads the same forward and backward.

Example:

s = "babad"
Output: "bab"   # "aba" is also valid
s = "cbbd"
Output: "bb"

✨ Flashcard

Front:
“How do we find the Longest Palindromic Substring efficiently?”

Back (short steps):

1️⃣ Expand around each character as a center
2️⃣ Check both odd and even length palindromes
3️⃣ Track the start and end indices of the longest palindrome
4️⃣ Return the substring using the indices

🧠 Key Idea

Every palindrome has a center. By expanding around all possible centers, we find the longest one:

Odd-length: expand around i

Even-length: expand around i and i+1

⚙️ DP / Expand Step 1 — Function Definition

class Solution:
    def longestPalindrome(self, s: str) -> str:

Inputs:

s: the string to analyze

Output:

Longest palindromic substring of s

🧱 Block 2 — Expand Function

        def expand(l, r):
            while l >= 0 and r < len(s) and s[l] == s[r]:
                l -= 1
                r += 1
            return l + 1, r - 1

Expands around indices l and r while characters match

Returns the actual start and end indices of the palindrome

🧱 Block 3 — Initialize Result Pointers

        start, end = 0, 0

start and end track the longest palindrome found

🧱 Block 4 — Loop Over All Centers

        for i in range(len(s)):
            l1, r1 = expand(i, i)      # odd-length palindrome
            l2, r2 = expand(i, i + 1)  # even-length palindrome

Check palindromes centered at i (odd)

Check palindromes between i and i+1 (even)

🧱 Block 5 — Update Longest Palindrome

            if r1 - l1 > end - start:
                start, end = l1, r1
            if r2 - l2 > end - start:
                start, end = l2, r2

Compare lengths and update start and end if a longer palindrome is found

🧱 Block 6 — Return Result

        return s[start:end + 1]

Slice the string to return the longest palindromic substring

📊 Time Complexity

O(N²) — expand from each of N centers, each may go up to N steps

📊 Space Complexity

O(1) — only a few pointers

🧠 Intuition Shortcut

Palindrome → expand around center

Odd + even centers cover all possibilities

Track longest seen


👉 Palindromic Substrings (LeetCode 647)

Return the total number of palindromic substrings in a string s.

A palindrome reads the same forward and backward.

A substring must be contiguous.

Example 1

s = "abc"

Output = 3

Palindromes:

"a"
"b"
"c"

Example 2

s = "aaa"

Output = 6

Palindromes:

"a"
"a"
"a"
"aa"
"aa"
"aaa"

✨ Flashcard

Front:
“How do we count all palindromic substrings?”

Back (short steps)

1️⃣ Treat every character as a center
2️⃣ Expand outward while characters match
3️⃣ Count every valid expansion
4️⃣ Check odd-length and even-length palindromes
5️⃣ Sum all counts

🧠 Key Idea

Every palindrome has a center.

Possible centers:

single character → odd palindrome

between characters → even palindrome

Example:

"aaa"

Centers:

a | a | a

and

a a
a a

Expand from each center and count palindromes.

⚙️ Algorithm Idea — Expand Around Center

For each index i:

expand(i, i)     → odd palindrome
expand(i, i+1)   → even palindrome

Every time characters match → count += 1

🧱 Block-by-Block Explanation

Block 1 — Function Definition
class Solution:
    def countSubstrings(self, s):

Input:

s → string

Output:

number of palindromic substrings
Block 2 — Expand Function
        def expand(l, r):
            count = 0
            while l >= 0 and r < len(s) and s[l] == s[r]:
                count += 1
                l -= 1
                r += 1
            return count

This function:

expands around center (l, r)

every successful expansion = one palindrome

Example:

s = "aaa"
center = 1

expansions:
"a"
"aaa"

Count increases each time.

Block 3 — Initialize Result
        ans = 0

Stores total number of palindromic substrings.

Block 4 — Check All Centers
        for i in range(len(s)):
            ans += expand(i, i)      # odd-length palindromes
            ans += expand(i, i + 1)  # even-length palindromes

We check:

Odd palindromes:

racecar
   ^

Even palindromes:

abba
  ^
Block 5 — Return Answer
        return ans

Return the total count.


📊 Time Complexity

O(N²)

Because we expand from every center.

Maximum:

1000 × 1000

Which is acceptable.

📦 Space Complexity

O(1)

No extra memory used.

